# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dynamo
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] In electricity generation, a **generator**, also called an **electric generator**, **electrical generator**, and **electromagnetic generator** is an electromechanical device that converts mechanical energy to electrical energy for use in an external circuit.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] In most generators which are rotating machines, a source of kinetic power rotates the generator's shaft, and the generator produces an electric current at its output terminals which flows through an external circuit, powering electrical loads.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Sources of mechanical energy used to drive generators include steam turbines, gas turbines, water turbines, internal combustion engines, wind turbines and even hand cranks.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Generators produce nearly all of the electric power for worldwide electric power grids.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] The first electromagnetic generator, the Faraday disk, was invented in 1831 by British scientist Michael Faraday.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] The reverse conversion of electrical energy into mechanical energy is done by an electric motor, and motors and generators are very similar.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Some motors can be used in a "backward" sense as generators, if their shaft is rotated they will generate electric power.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] In addition to its most common usage for electromechanical generators described above, the term generator is also used for photovoltaic, fuel cell, and magnetohydrodynamic powered devices that use solar power and chemical fuels, respectively, to generate electrical power.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Electromagnetic generators fall into one of two broad categories, dynamos and alternators.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] The armature can be on either the rotor or the stator, depending on the design, with the field coil or magnet on the other part.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Before the connection between magnetism and electricity was discovered, electrostatic generators were invented.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] They operated on electrostatic principles, by using moving electrically charged belts, plates and disks that carried charge to a high potential electrode.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] The charge was generated using either of two mechanisms: electrostatic induction or the triboelectric effect.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Such generators generated very high voltage and low current.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Because of their inefficiency and the difficulty of insulating machines that produced very high voltages, electrostatic generators had low power ratings, and were never used for generation of commercially significant quantities of electric power.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Their only practical applications were to power early X-ray tubes, and later in some atomic particle accelerators.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] The operating principle of electromagnetic generators was discovered in the years of 1831–1832 by Michael Faraday.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] The principle, later called Faraday's law of induction, is that an electromotive force is generated in an electrical conductor which encircles a varying magnetic flux.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Faraday also built the first electromagnetic generator, called the Faraday disk; a type of homopolar generator, using a copper disc rotating between the poles of a horseshoe magnet.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] This design was inefficient, due to self-cancelling counterflows of current in regions of the disk that were not under the influence of the magnetic field.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] While current was induced directly underneath the magnet, the current would circulate backwards in regions that were outside the influence of the magnetic field.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] This counterflow limited the power output to the pickup wires and induced waste heating of the copper disc.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Later homopolar generators would solve this problem by using an array of magnets arranged around the disc perimeter to maintain a steady field effect in one current-flow direction.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Another disadvantage was that the output voltage was very low, due to the single current path through the magnetic flux.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Experimenters found that using multiple turns of wire in a coil could produce higher, more useful voltages.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Since the output voltage is proportional to the number of turns, generators could be easily designed to produce any desired voltage by varying the number of turns.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Wire windings became a basic feature of all subsequent generator designs.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Independently of Faraday, Ányos Jedlik started experimenting in 1827 with the electromagnetic rotating devices which he called electromagnetic self-rotors.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] In the prototype of the single-pole electric starter (finished between 1852 and 1854) both the stationary and the revolving parts were electromagnetic.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] It was also the discovery of the principle of dynamo self-excitation, which replaced permanent magnet designs.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] He also may have formulated the concept of the dynamo in 1861 (before Siemens and Wheatstone) but did not patent it as he thought he was not the first to realize this.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] A coil of wire rotating in a magnetic field produces a current which changes direction with each 180° rotation, an alternating current (AC).
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] However many early uses of electricity required direct current (DC).
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] In the first practical electric generators, called *dynamos*, the AC was converted into DC with a *commutator*, a set of rotating switch contacts on the armature shaft.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] The commutator reversed the connection of the armature winding to the circuit every 180° rotation of the shaft, creating a pulsing DC current.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] One of the first dynamos was built by Hippolyte Pixii in 1832.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] The dynamo was the first electrical generator capable of delivering power for industry.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] The Woolrich Electrical Generator of 1844, now in Thinktank, Birmingham Science Museum, is the earliest electrical generator used in an industrial process.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] It was used by the firm of Elkingtons for commercial electroplating.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] The modern dynamo, fit for use in industrial applications, was invented independently by Sir Charles Wheatstone, Werner von Siemens and Samuel Alfred Varley.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Varley took out a patent on 24 December 1866, while Siemens and Wheatstone both announced their discoveries on 17 January 1867 by delivering papers at the Royal Society.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] The "dynamo-electric machine" employed self-powering electromagnetic field coils rather than permanent magnets to create the stator field.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Wheatstone's design was similar to Siemens', with the difference that in the Siemens design the stator electromagnets were in series with the rotor, but in Wheatstone's design they were in parallel.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] The use of electromagnets rather than permanent magnets greatly increased the power output of a dynamo and enabled high power generation for the first time.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] This invention led directly to the first major industrial uses of electricity.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] For example, in the 1870s Siemens used electromagnetic dynamos to power electric arc furnaces for the production of metals and other materials.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] The dynamo machine that was developed consisted of a stationary structure, which provides the magnetic field, and a set of rotating windings which turn within that field.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] On larger machines the constant magnetic field is provided by one or more electromagnets, which are usually called field coils.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Large power generation dynamos are now rarely seen due to the now nearly universal use of alternating current for power distribution.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Before the adoption of AC, very large direct-current dynamos were the only means of power generation and distribution.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] AC has come to dominate due to the ability of AC to be easily transformed to and from very high voltages to permit low losses over large distances.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Through a series of discoveries, the dynamo was succeeded by many later inventions, especially the AC alternator, which was capable of generating alternating current.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] It is commonly known to be the Synchronous Generators (SGs).
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] The synchronous machines are directly connected to the grid and need to be properly synchronized during startup.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Moreover, they are excited with special control to enhance the stability of the power system.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Alternating current generating systems were known in simple forms from Michael Faraday's original discovery of the magnetic induction of electric current.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Faraday himself built an early alternator.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] His machine was a "rotating rectangle", whose operation was *heteropolar*: each active conductor passed successively through regions where the magnetic field was in opposite directions.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Large two-phase alternating current generators were built by a British electrician, J.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] The first public demonstration of an "alternator system" was given by William Stanley Jr., an employee of Westinghouse Electric in 1886.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Sebastian Ziani de Ferranti established *Ferranti, Thompson and Ince* in 1882, to market his *Ferranti-Thompson Alternator*, invented with the help of renowned physicist Lord Kelvin.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] His early alternators produced frequencies between 100 and 300 Hz.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Ferranti went on to design the Deptford Power Station for the London Electric Supply Corporation in 1887 using an alternating current system.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] On its completion in 1891, it was the first truly modern power station, supplying high-voltage AC power that was then "stepped down" for consumer use on each street.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] This basic system remains in use today around the world.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] After 1891, polyphase alternators were introduced to supply currents of multiple differing phases.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Later alternators were designed for varying alternating-current frequencies between sixteen and about one hundred hertz, for use with arc lighting, incandescent lighting and electric motors.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] As the requirements for larger scale power generation increased, a new limitation rose: the magnetic fields available from permanent magnets.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Diverting a small amount of the power generated by the generator to an electromagnetic field coil mounted on the rotor allowed the generator to produce substantially more power.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] This concept was dubbed self-excitation.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] The field coils are connected in series or parallel with the armature winding.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] When the generator first starts to turn, the small amount of remanent magnetism present in the iron core provides a magnetic field to get it started, generating a small current in the armature.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] This flows through the field coils, creating a larger magnetic field which generates a larger armature current.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] This "bootstrap" process continues until the magnetic field in the core levels off due to saturation and the generator reaches a steady state power output.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Very large power station generators often utilize a separate smaller generator to excite the field coils of the larger.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] In the event of a severe widespread power outage where islanding of power stations has occurred, the stations may need to perform a black start to excite the fields of their largest generators, in order to restore customer power service.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] A dynamo uses commutators to produce direct current.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] It is self-excited, i.e. its field electromagnets are powered by the machine's own output.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Other types of DC generators use a separate source of direct current to energize their field magnets.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] A homopolar generator is a DC electrical generator comprising an electrically conductive disc or cylinder rotating in a plane perpendicular to a uniform static magnetic field.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] A potential difference is created between the center of the disc and the rim (or ends of the cylinder), the electrical polarity depending on the direction of rotation and the orientation of the field.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] It is also known as a **unipolar generator**, **acyclic generator**, **disk dynamo**, or **Faraday disc**.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] The voltage is typically low, on the order of a few volts in the case of small demonstration models, but large research generators can produce hundreds of volts, and some systems have multiple generators in series to produce an even larger voltage.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] They are unusual in that they can produce tremendous electric current, some more than a million amperes, because the homopolar generator can be made to have very low internal resistance.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] A magnetohydrodynamic generator directly extracts electric power from moving hot gases through a magnetic field, without the use of rotating electromagnetic machinery.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] MHD generators were originally developed because the output of a plasma MHD generator is a flame, well able to heat the boilers of a steam power plant.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] The first practical design was the AVCO Mk.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] The U.S. government funded substantial development, culminating in a 25 MW demonstration plant in 1987.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] In the Soviet Union from 1972 until the late 1980s, the MHD plant U 25 was in regular utility operation on the Moscow power system with a rating of 25 MW, the largest MHD plant rating in the world at that time.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] MHD generators operated as a topping cycle are currently (2007) less efficient than combined cycle gas turbines.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Induction AC motors may be used as generators, turning mechanical energy into electric current.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Induction generators operate by mechanically turning their rotor faster than the simultaneous speed, giving negative slip.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] A regular AC non-simultaneous motor usually can be used as a generator, without any changes to its parts.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Induction generators are useful in applications like minihydro power plants, wind turbines, or in reducing high-pressure gas streams to lower pressure, because they can recover energy with relatively simple controls.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] They do not require another circuit to start working because the turning magnetic field is provided by induction from the one they have.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] They also do not require speed governor equipment as they inherently operate at the connected grid frequency.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] An induction generator must be powered with a leading voltage; this is usually done by connection to an electrical grid, or by powering themselves with phase correcting capacitors.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] In the simplest form of linear electric generator, a sliding magnet moves back and forth through a solenoid, a copper wire or a coil.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] An alternating current is induced in the wire, or loops of wire, by Faraday's law of induction each time the magnet slides through.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] This type of generator is used in the Faraday flashlight.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Larger linear electricity generators are used in wave power schemes.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Grid-connected generators deliver power at a constant frequency.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] For generators of the synchronous or induction type, the prime mover speed turning the generator shaft must be at a particular speed (or narrow range of speed) to deliver power at the required utility frequency.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Mechanical speed-regulating devices may waste a significant fraction of the input energy to maintain a required fixed frequency.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Where it is impractical or undesired to tightly regulate the speed of the prime mover, doubly fed electric machines may be used as generators.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] With the assistance of power electronic devices, these can regulate the output frequency to a desired value over a wider range of generator shaft speeds.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Alternatively, a standard generator can be used with no attempt to regulate frequency, and the resulting power converted to the desired output frequency with a rectifier and converter combination.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Allowing a wider range of prime mover speeds can improve the overall energy production of an installation, at the cost of more complex generators and controls.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] For example, where a wind turbine operating at fixed frequency might be required to spill energy at high wind speeds, a variable speed system can allow recovery of energy contained during periods of high wind speed.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] A *power station*, also known as a *power plant* or *powerhouse* and sometimes *generating station* or *generating plant*, is an industrial facility that generates electricity.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Most power stations contain one or more generators, or spinning machines converting mechanical power into three-phase electrical power.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] The relative motion between a magnetic field and a conductor creates an electric current.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] The energy source harnessed to turn the generator varies widely.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Most power stations in the world burn fossil fuels such as coal, oil, and natural gas to generate electricity.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Cleaner sources include nuclear power, and increasingly use renewables such as the sun, wind, waves and running water.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Motor vehicles require electrical energy to power their instrumentation, keep the engine itself operating, and recharge their batteries.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Until about the 1960s motor vehicles tended to use DC generators (dynamos) with electromechanical regulators.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Following the historical trend above and for many of the same reasons, these have now been replaced by alternators with built-in rectifier circuits.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Bicycles require energy to power running lights and other equipment.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] There are two common kinds of generator in use on bicycles: bottle dynamos which engage the bicycle's tire on an as-needed basis, and hub dynamos which are directly attached to the bicycle's drive train.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] The name is conventional as they are small permanent-magnet alternators, not self-excited DC machines as are dynamos.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Some electric bicycles are capable of regenerative braking, where the drive motor is used as a generator to recover some energy during braking.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Sailing boats may use a water- or wind-powered generator to trickle-charge the batteries.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] A small propeller, wind turbine or turbine is connected to a low-power generator to supply currents at typical wind or cruising speeds.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Recreational vehicles need an extra power supply to power their onboard accessories, including air conditioning units, and refrigerators.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] An RV power plug is connected to the electric generator to obtain a stable power supply.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Electric scooters with regenerative braking have become popular all over the world.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Engineers use kinetic energy recovery systems on the scooter to reduce energy consumption and increase its range up to 40-60% by simply recovering energy using the magnetic brake, which generates electric energy for further use.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Modern vehicles reach speed up to 25–30 km/h and can run up to 35–40 km.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] An *engine–generator* is the combination of an electrical generator and an engine (prime mover) mounted together to form a single piece of self-contained equipment.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] The engines used are usually piston engines, but gas turbines can also be used, and there are even hybrid diesel-gas units, called dual-fuel units.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Many different versions of engine–generators are available – ranging from very small portable petrol powered sets to large turbine installations.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] The primary advantage of engine–generators is the ability to independently supply electricity, allowing the units to serve as backup power sources.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] A generator can also be driven by human muscle power (for instance, in field radio station equipment).
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Human powered electric generators are commercially available, and have been the project of some DIY enthusiasts.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Typically operated by means of pedal power, a converted bicycle trainer, or a foot pump, such generators can be practically used to charge batteries, and in some cases are designed with an integral inverter.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] An average "healthy human" can produce a steady 75 watts (0.1 horsepower) for a full eight hour period, while a "first class athlete" can produce approximately 298 watts (0.4 horsepower) for a similar period, at the end of which an undetermined period of rest and recovery will be required.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] At 298 watts, the average "healthy human" becomes exhausted within 10 minutes.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] The net electrical power that can be produced will be less due to the inefficiency of the generator.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Portable radio receivers with cranks are made to reduce battery purchase requirements; see Clockwork radio.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] During the mid 20th century, pedal-powered radios were used throughout the Australian outback, to provide schooling (School of the Air), medical and other needs in remote stations and towns.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] A tachogenerator is an electromechanical device which produces an output voltage proportional to its shaft speed.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] It may be used for a speed indicator or in a feedback speed control system.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Tachogenerators are frequently used to power tachometers to measure the speeds of electric motors, engines, and the equipment they power.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] Generators generate voltage roughly proportional to shaft speed.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] With precise construction and design, generators can be built to produce very precise voltages for certain ranges of shaft speeds.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] An equivalent circuit of a generator and load is shown in the adjacent diagram.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] The generator is represented by an abstract generator consisting of an ideal voltage source and an internal impedance.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] The generator's $V_{\text{G}}$ and $R_{\text{G}}$ parameters can be determined by measuring the winding resistance (corrected to operating temperature), and measuring the open-circuit and loaded voltage for a defined current load.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] This is the simplest model of a generator, further elements may need to be added for an accurate representation.
[src:dynamo/ac-generator] In particular, inductance can be added to allow for the machine's windings and magnetic leakage flux, but a full representation can become much more complex than this.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] An **AC motor** is an electric motor driven by an alternating current (AC).
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The AC motor commonly consists of two basic parts, an outside stator having coils supplied with alternating current to produce a rotating magnetic field, and an inside rotor attached to the output shaft producing a second rotating magnetic field.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The rotor magnetic field may be produced by permanent magnets, reluctance saliency, or DC or AC electrical windings.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Less common, AC linear motors operate on similar principles as rotating motors but have their stationary and moving parts arranged in a straight line configuration, producing linear motion instead of rotation.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The two main types of AC motors are induction motors and synchronous motors.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The induction motor (or asynchronous motor) always relies on a small difference in speed between the stator rotating magnetic field and the rotor shaft speed called slip to induce rotor current in the rotor AC winding.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] As a result, the induction motor cannot produce torque near synchronous speed where induction (or slip) is irrelevant or ceases to exist.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] In contrast, the synchronous motor does not rely on slip-induction for operation and uses either permanent magnets, salient poles (having projecting magnetic poles), or an independently excited rotor winding.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The synchronous motor produces its rated torque at exactly synchronous speed.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The brushless wound-rotor doubly fed synchronous motor system has an independently excited rotor winding that does not rely on the principles of slip-induction of current.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The brushless wound-rotor doubly fed motor is a synchronous motor that can function exactly at the supply frequency or sub to super multiple of the supply frequency.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Other types of motors include eddy current motors, and AC and DC mechanically commutated machines in which speed is dependent on voltage and winding connection.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Alternating current technology was rooted in Michael Faraday's and Joseph Henry's 1830–31 discovery that a changing magnetic field can induce an electric current in a circuit.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Faraday is usually given credit for this discovery since he published his findings first.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] In 1832, French instrument maker Hippolyte Pixii generated a crude form of alternating current when he designed and built the first alternator.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] It consisted of a revolving horseshoe magnet passing over two wound-wire coils.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Because of AC's advantages in long-distance high voltage transmission, there were many inventors in the United States and Europe during the late 19th century trying to develop workable AC motors.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The first person to conceive of a rotating magnetic field was Walter Baily, who gave a workable demonstration of his battery-operated polyphase motor aided by a commutator on 28 June 1879, to the Physical Society of London.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Describing an apparatus nearly identical to Baily's, French electrical engineer Marcel Deprez published a paper in 1880 that identified the rotating magnetic field principle and that of a two-phase AC system of currents to produce it.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Never practically demonstrated, the design was flawed, as one of the two currents was “furnished by the machine itself.” In 1886, English-born American engineer Elihu Thomson built an AC motor by expanding upon the induction-repulsion principle and his wattmeter.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] In 1887, American inventor Charles Schenk Bradley was the first to patent a two-phase AC power transmission with four wires.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] "Commutatorless" alternating current induction motors seem to have been independently invented by Galileo Ferraris and Nikola Tesla.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] In 1888, Ferraris published his research to the Royal Academy of Sciences in Turin, where he detailed the foundations of motor operation; Tesla, in the same year, was granted a United States patent for his own motor.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Working from Ferraris's experiments, Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrovolsky introduced the first three-phase induction motor in 1890, a much more capable design that became the prototype used in Europe and the U.S.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] He also invented the first three-phase generator and transformer and combined them into the first complete AC three-phase system in 1891.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The three-phase motor design was also worked on by the Swiss engineer Charles Eugene Lancelot Brown, and other three-phase AC systems were developed by German technician Friedrich August Haselwander and Swedish engineer Jonas Wenström.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] If the rotor of a squirrel cage motor were to run at the true synchronous speed, the flux in the rotor at any given place on the rotor would not change, and no current would be created in the squirrel cage.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] For this reason, ordinary squirrel-cage motors run at some tens of revolutions per minute (RPM) slower than synchronous speed.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Because the rotating field (or equivalent pulsating field) effectively rotates faster than the rotor, it could be said to *slip* past the surface of the rotor.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The difference between synchronous speed and actual speed is called **slip**, and loading the motor increases the amount of slip as the motor slows down slightly.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Even with no load, internal mechanical losses prevent the slip from being zero.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The constant 120 results from combining the conversions of 60 seconds per minute and that each phase requires 2 poles.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Actual RPM for an induction motor will be less than this calculated synchronous speed by an amount known as *slip*, that increases with the torque produced.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] With no load, the speed will be very close to synchronous.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] When loaded, standard motors have between 2–3% slip, special motors may have up to 7% slip, and a class of motors known as *torque motors* are rated to operate at 100% slip (i.e., 0 rpm, full stall).
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] As an example, a typical four-pole motor running on 60 Hz might have a nameplate rating of 1725 rpm at full load, while its calculated speed is 1800 rpm.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The speed in this type of motor has traditionally been altered by having additional sets of coils or poles in the motor that can be switched on and off to change the speed of magnetic field rotation.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] However, developments in power electronics mean that the frequency of the power supply can also now be varied to provide a smoother control of the motor speed.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] This kind of rotor is the basic hardware for induction regulators, which is an exception of the use of rotating magnetic field as pure electrical (not electromechanical) application.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Most common AC motors use the squirrel-cage rotor, which will be found in virtually all domestic and light industrial alternating current motors.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The squirrel-cage refers to the rotating exercise cage for pet animals.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The motor takes its name from the shape of its rotor "windings"- a ring at either end of the rotor, with bars connecting the rings running the length of the rotor.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] It is typically cast aluminum or copper poured between the iron laminates of the rotor, and usually only the end rings will be visible.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The vast majority of the rotor currents will flow through the bars rather than the higher-resistance and usually varnished laminates.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Very low voltages at very high currents are typical in the bars and end rings; high efficiency motors will often use cast copper to reduce the resistance in the rotor.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] In operation, the squirrel-cage motor may be viewed as a transformer with a rotating secondary.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] When the rotor is not rotating in sync with the magnetic field, large rotor currents are induced; the large rotor currents magnetize the rotor and interact with the stator's magnetic fields to bring the rotor almost into synchronization with the stator's field.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] An unloaded squirrel-cage motor at rated no-load speed will consume electrical power only to maintain rotor speed against friction and resistance losses.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] As the mechanical load increases, so will the electrical load – the electrical load is inherently related to the mechanical load.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] This is similar to a transformer, where the primary's electrical load is related to the secondary's electrical load.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] This is why a squirrel-cage blower motor may cause household lights to dim upon starting, but does not dim the lights on startup when its fan belt (and therefore mechanical load) is removed.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Furthermore, a stalled squirrel-cage motor (overloaded or with a jammed shaft) will consume current limited only by circuit resistance as it attempts to start.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Unless something else limits the current (or cuts it off completely) overheating and destruction of the winding insulation is the likely outcome.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Many washing machines, dishwashers, larger standalone fans, compressors, etc. use some variant of a squirrel-cage motor.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] An alternate design, called the wound rotor motor, is used when variable speed is required.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] In this case, the rotor has the same number of poles as the stator and the windings are made of wire, connected to slip rings on the shaft.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Carbon brushes connect the slip rings to a controller such as a variable resistor that allows changing the motor's slip rate.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] In certain high-power variable-speed wound rotor drives, the slip-frequency energy is captured, rectified, and returned to the power supply through an inverter.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] With bidirectionally controlled power, the wound rotor becomes an active participant in the energy conversion process, with the wound rotor doubly fed configuration showing twice the power density.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Compared to squirrel cage rotors, wound rotor motors are expensive and require maintenance of the slip rings and brushes, but they were the standard form for variable speed control before the advent of compact power electronic devices.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Transistorized inverters with variable-frequency drive can now be used for speed control, and wound rotor motors are becoming less common.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Several methods of starting a polyphase motor are used.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Where a large inrush current and high starting torque can be permitted, the motor can be started across the line, by applying full line voltage to the terminals (direct-on-line, DOL).
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Where it is necessary to limit the starting inrush current (where the motor is large compared with the short-circuit capacity of the supply), the motor is started at reduced voltage using either series inductors, an autotransformer, thyristors, or other devices.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] A technique sometimes used is star-delta (YΔ) starting, where the motor coils are initially connected in star configuration for acceleration of the load, then switched to delta configuration when the load is up to speed.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] This technique is more common in Europe than in North America.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Transistorized drives can directly vary the applied voltage as required by the starting characteristics of the motor and load.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] This type of motor is becoming more common in traction applications such as locomotives, where it is known as the asynchronous traction motor.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] 2. a control-voltage (AC) winding in quadrature (i.e., 90 degrees phase shifted) with the main winding so as to produce a rotating magnetic field.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Reversing phase makes the motor reverse.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] An AC servo amplifier, a linear power amplifier, feeds the control winding.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The electrical resistance of the rotor is made high intentionally so that the speed–torque curve is fairly linear.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Two-phase servo motors are inherently high-speed, low-torque devices, heavily geared down to drive the load.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Single-phase motors do not have a unique rotating magnetic field like multi-phase motors.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The field alternates (reverses polarity) between pole pairs and can be viewed as two fields rotating in opposite directions.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] They require a secondary magnetic field that causes the rotor to move in a specific direction.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] After starting, the alternating stator field is in relative rotation with the rotor.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] A common single-phase motor is the shaded-pole motor and is used in devices requiring low starting torque, such as electric fans, small pumps, or small household appliances.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] In this motor, small single-turn copper "shading coils" create the moving magnetic field.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Part of each pole is encircled by a copper coil or strap; the induced current in the strap opposes the change of flux through the coil.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] This causes a time lag in the flux passing through the shading coil, so that the maximum field intensity moves higher across the pole face on each cycle.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] This produces a low level rotating magnetic field which is large enough to turn both the rotor and its attached load.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] As the rotor picks up speed the torque builds up to its full level as the principal magnetic field is rotating relative to the rotating rotor.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] A **reversible shaded-pole motor** was made by Barber-Colman several decades ago.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] It had a single field coil, and two principal poles, each split halfway to create two pairs of poles.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Each of these four "half-poles" carried a coil, and the coils of diagonally opposite half-poles were connected to a pair of terminals.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] One terminal of each pair was common, so only three terminals were needed in all.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The motor would not start with the terminals open; connecting the common to one made the motor run one way, and connecting the common to the other made it run the other way.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] These motors were used in industrial and scientific devices.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] An unusual, **adjustable-speed**, low-torque shaded-pole motor could be found in traffic-light and advertising-lighting controllers.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The pole faces were parallel and relatively close to each other, with the disc centered between them, something like the disc in a watthour electricity meter.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Each pole face was split, and had a shading coil on one part; the shading coils were on the parts that faced each other.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Applying AC to the coil created a field that progressed in the gap between the poles.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The plane of the stator core was approximately tangential to an imaginary circle on the disc, so the travelling magnetic field dragged the disc and made it rotate.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The stator was mounted on a pivot so it could be positioned for the desired speed and then clamped in position.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Placing the poles nearer to the center of the disc made it run faster, and toward the edge, slower.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Another common single-phase AC motor is the *split-phase induction motor*, commonly used in major appliances such as air conditioners and clothes dryers.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Compared to the shaded pole motor, these motors provide much greater starting torque.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] A split-phase motor has a secondary startup winding that is 90 electrical degrees to the main winding, always centered directly between the poles of the main winding, and connected to the main winding by a set of electrical contacts.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The coils of this winding are wound with fewer turns of smaller wire than the main winding, so it has a lower inductance and higher resistance.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The position of the winding creates a small phase shift between the flux of the main winding and the flux of the starting winding, causing the rotor to rotate.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] When the speed of the motor is sufficient to overcome the inertia of the load, the contacts are opened automatically by a centrifugal switch or electric relay.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The direction of rotation is determined by the connection between the main winding and the start circuit.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] In applications where the motor requires a fixed rotation, one end of the start circuit is permanently connected to the main winding, with the contacts making the connection at the other end.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] A capacitor start motor is a split-phase induction motor with a starting motor capacitor inserted in series with the startup winding, creating an LC circuit which produces a greater phase shift (and so, a much greater starting torque) than both split-phase and shaded pole motors.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] This motor has a centrifugal switch which disconnects the capacitor once the motor has started.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] This motor provides high starting torque.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] This motor provides high starting torque and high efficiency.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] A resistance start motor is a split-phase induction motor with a starter inserted in series with the startup winding, creating reactance.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] This added starter provides assistance in the starting and initial direction of rotation.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The start winding is made mainly of thin wire with fewer turns to make it high resistive and less inductive.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The main winding is made with thicker wire with larger number of turns which makes it less resistive and more inductive.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Another variation is the *permanent-split capacitor (or PSC) motor*.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Also known as a capacitor-run motor, this type of motor uses a non-polarized capacitor with a high voltage rating to generate an electrical phase shift between the run and start windings.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] PSC motors are the dominant type of split-phase motor in Europe and much of the world, but in North America, they are most frequently used in variable torque applications (like blowers, fans, and pumps) and other cases where variable speeds are desired.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] A capacitor with a relatively low capacitance, and relatively high voltage rating, is connected in series with the start winding and remains in the circuit during the entire run cycle.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Like other split-phase motors, the main winding is used with a smaller start winding, and rotation is changed by reversing the connection between the main winding and the start circuit, or by having polarity of main winding switched while start winding is always connected to a capacitor.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] There are significant differences, however; the use of a speed sensitive centrifugal switch requires that other split-phase motors must operate at, or very close to, full speed.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] PSC motors may operate within a wide range of speeds, much lower than the motor's electrical speed.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Also, for applications like automatic door openers that require the motor to reverse rotation often, the use of a mechanism requires that a motor must slow to a near stop before contact with the start winding is re-established.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The 'permanent' connection to the capacitor in a PSC motor means that changing rotation is instantaneous.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Three-phase motors can be converted to PSC motors by making common two windings and connecting the third via a capacitor to act as a start winding.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] However, the power rating needs to be at least 50% larger than for a comparable single-phase motor due to an unused winding.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The synchronous motor can also be used as an alternator.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Contemporary synchronous motors are frequently driven by solid state variable-frequency drives.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] This greatly eases the problem of starting the massive rotor of a large synchronous motor.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Synchronous motors are occasionally used as traction motors; the TGV may be the best-known example of such use.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Huge numbers of three phase synchronous motors are now fitted to electric cars.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] They have a neodymium or other rare-earth permanent magnet.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] One use for this type of motor is its use in a power factor correction scheme.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] They are referred to as synchronous condensers.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] This exploits a feature of the machine where it consumes power at a leading power factor when its rotor is over excited.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] It thus appears to the supply to be a capacitor, and could thus be used to correct the lagging power factor that is usually presented to the electric supply by inductive loads.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The excitation is adjusted until a near unity power factor is obtained (often automatically).
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Machines used for this purpose are easily identified as they have no shaft extensions.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Synchronous motors are valued in any case because their power factor is much better than that of induction motors, making them preferred for very high power applications.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Some of the largest AC motors are pumped-storage hydroelectricity generators that are operated as synchronous motors to pump water to a reservoir at a higher elevation for later use to generate electricity using the same machinery.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Six 500-megawatt generators are installed in the Bath County Pumped Storage Station in Virginia, USA.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] When pumping, each unit can produce 642,800 horsepower (479.3 megawatts).
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Small single-phase AC motors can also be designed with magnetized rotors (or several variations on that idea; see "Hysteresis synchronous motors" below).
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] If a conventional squirrel-cage rotor has flats ground on it to create salient poles and increase reluctance, it will start conventionally, but will run synchronously, although it can provide only a modest torque at synchronous speed.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Because inertia makes it difficult to instantly accelerate the rotor from stopped to synchronous speed, these motors normally require some sort of special feature to get started.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Some include a squirrel-cage structure to bring the rotor close to synchronous speed.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Various other designs use a small induction motor (which may share the same field coils and rotor as the synchronous motor) or a very light rotor with a one-way mechanism (to ensure that the rotor starts in the "forward" direction).
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] In the latter instance, applying AC power creates chaotic (or seemingly chaotic) jumping movement back and forth; such a motor will always start, but lacking the anti-reversal mechanism, the direction it runs is unpredictable.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The Hammond organ tone generator used a non-self-starting synchronous motor (until comparatively recently), and had an auxiliary conventional shaded-pole starting motor.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] A spring-loaded auxiliary manual starting switch connected power to this second motor for a few seconds.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] These motors are relatively costly, and are used where exact speed (assuming an exact-frequency AC source) and rotation with low flutter (high-frequency variation in speed) are essential.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Applications included tape recorder capstan drives (the motor shaft could be the capstan), and, before the advent of crystal control, motion picture cameras and recorders.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Their distinguishing feature is their rotor, which is a smooth cylinder of a magnetic alloy that stays magnetized, but can be demagnetized fairly easily as well as re-magnetized with poles in a new location.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Hysteresis refers to how the magnetic flux in the metal lags behind the external magnetizing force; for instance, to demagnetize such a material, one could apply a magnetizing field of opposite polarity to that which originally magnetized the material.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] These motors have a stator like those of capacitor-run squirrel-cage induction motors.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] On startup, when slip decreases sufficiently, the rotor becomes magnetized by the stator's field, and the poles stay in place.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The motor then runs at synchronous speed as if the rotor were a permanent magnet.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] When stopped and restarted, the poles are likely to form at different locations.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] For a given design, torque at synchronous speed is only relatively modest, and the motor can run at below synchronous speed.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] In simple words, it is lagging magnetic field behind magnetic flux.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] A universal motor is a design that can operate on either AC or DC power.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] In universal motors the stator and rotor of a brushed DC motor are both wound and supplied from an external source, with the torque being a function of the rotor current times the stator current so reversing the current in both rotor and stator does not reverse the rotation.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Universal motors can run on AC as well as DC provided the frequency is not so high that the inductive reactance of the stator winding and eddy current losses become problems.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Nearly all universal motors are series-wound because their stators have relatively few turns, minimizing inductance.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Universal motors are compact, have high starting torque and can be varied in speed over a wide range with relatively simple controls such as rheostats and PWM choppers.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Compared with induction motors, universal motors do have some drawbacks inherent to their brushes and commutators: relatively high levels of electrical and acoustic noise, low reliability and more frequent required maintenance.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Universal motors are widely used in small home appliances and hand power tools.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Until the 1970s they dominated electric traction (electric, including diesel-electric railway and road vehicles); many traction power networks still use special low frequencies such as 16.7 and 25 Hz to overcome the aforementioned problems with losses and reactance.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Still widely used, universal traction motors have been increasingly displaced by polyphase AC induction and permanent magnet motors with variable-frequency drives made possible by modern power semiconductor devices.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Repulsion motors are wound-rotor single-phase AC motors that are a type of induction motor.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] In a repulsion motor, the armature brushes are shorted together rather than connected in series with the field, as is done with universal motors.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] By transformer action, the stator induces currents in the rotor, which create torque by repulsion instead of attraction as in other motors.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Several types of repulsion motors have been manufactured, but the *repulsion-start induction-run* (RS-IR) motor has been used most frequently.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The RS-IR motor has a centrifugal switch that shorts all segments of the commutator so that the motor operates as an induction motor once it is close to full speed.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Some of these motors also lift the brushes out of contact with source voltage regulation.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Repulsion motors were developed before suitable motor starting capacitors were available, and few repulsion motors are sold as of 2005.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Where speed stability is important, some AC motors (such as some Papst motors) have the stator on the inside and the rotor on the outside to optimize inertia and cooling.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Exterior rotors are also common in ceiling fan motors.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] A conical rotor brake motor incorporates the brake as an integral part of the conical sliding rotor.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] When the motor is at rest, a spring acts on the sliding rotor and forces the brake ring against the brake cap in the motor, holding the rotor stationary.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] When the motor is energized, its magnetic field generates both an axial and a radial component.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The axial component overcomes the spring force, releasing the brake; while the radial component causes the rotor to turn.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] There is no additional brake control required.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The high starting torque and low inertia of the conical rotor brake motor has proven to be ideal for the demands of high cycle dynamic drives in applications since the motor was invented, designed and introduced over 50 years ago.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] This type of motor configuration was first introduced in the US in 1963.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Single-speed or two speed motors are designed for coupling to gear motor system gearboxes.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Conical rotor brake motors are also used to power micro speed drives.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Motors of this type can also be found on overhead cranes and hoists.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The micro speed unit combines two motors and an intermediate gear reducer.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] These are used for applications where extreme mechanical positioning accuracy and high cycling capability are needed.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The micro speed unit combines a “main” conical rotor brake motor for rapid speed and a “micro” conical rotor brake motor for slow or positioning speed.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The intermediate gearbox allows a range of ratios, and motors of different speeds can be combined to produce high ratios between high and low speed.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Electronically commutated (EC) motors are electric motors powered by direct-current (DC) electricity and having electronic commutation systems, rather than mechanical commutators and brushes.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The current-to-torque and frequency-to-speed relationships of BLDC motors are linear.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] While the motor coils are powered by DC, power may be rectified from AC within the casing.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] These are two-phase induction motors with permanent magnets to retard the rotor so its speed is accurately proportional to the power passing through the meter.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The rotor is an aluminium-alloy disc, and currents induced into it react with the field from the stator.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] A split-phase watthour electricity meter has a stator with three coils facing the disc.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The magnetic circuit is completed by a C-shaped core of permeable iron.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The "voltage" coil above the disc is in parallel with the supply; its many turns have a high inductance/resistance ratio (Q) so its current and magnetic field are the time integral of the applied voltage, lagging it by 90 degrees.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] This magnetic field passes down perpendicularly through the disc, inducing circular eddy currents in the plane of the disc centered on the field.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] These induced currents are proportional to the time derivative of the magnetic field, leading it by 90 degrees.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] This puts the eddy currents in phase with the voltage applied to the voltage coil, just as the current induced in the secondary of a transformer with a resistive load is in phase with the voltage applied to its primary.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The eddy currents pass directly above the pole pieces of two "current" coils under the disc, each wound with a few turns of heavy-gauge wire whose inductive reactance is small compared to the load impedance.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] These coils connect the supply to the load, producing a magnetic field in phase with the load current.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] This field passes from the pole of one current coil up perpendicularly through the disc and back down through the disc to the pole of the other current coil, with a completed magnetic circuit back to the first current coil.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] As these fields cross the disc, they pass through the eddy currents induced in it by the voltage coil producing a Lorentz force on the disc mutually perpendicular to both.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Assuming power is flowing to the load, the flux from the left current coil crosses the disc upwards where the eddy current flows radially toward the center of the disc producing (by the right-hand rule) a torque driving the front of the disc to the right.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Similarly, the flux crosses down through the disc to the right current coil where the eddy current flows radially away from the disc center, again producing a torque driving the front of the disc to the right.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] When the AC polarity reverses, the eddy currents in the disc and the direction of the magnetic flux from the current coils both change, leaving the direction of the torque unchanged.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The torque is thus proportional to the instantaneous line voltage times the instantaneous load current, automatically correcting for power factor.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The disc is braked by a permanent magnet so that speed is proportional to torque and the disc mechanically integrates real power.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The mechanical dial on the meter reads disc rotations and the total net energy delivered to the load.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] In a split-phase watthour meter the voltage coil is connected between the two "hot" (line) terminals (240 V in North America) and two separate current coils are connected between the corresponding line and load terminals.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] No connection to the system neutral is needed to correctly handle combined line-to-neutral and line-to-line loads.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Line-to-line loads draw the same current through both current coils and spin the meter twice as fast as a line-to-neutral load drawing the same current through only a single current coil, correctly registering the power drawn by the line-to-line load as twice that of the line-to-neutral load.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Other variations of the same design are used for polyphase (e.g., three-phase) power.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Representative are low-torque synchronous motors with a multi-pole hollow cylindrical magnet (internal poles) surrounding the stator structure.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The stator has one coil, coaxial with the shaft.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] At each end of the coil are a pair of circular plates with rectangular teeth on their edges, formed so they are parallel with the shaft.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] One of the pair of discs distributes the coil's flux directly, while the other receives flux that has passed through a common shading coil.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] The poles are rather narrow, and between the poles leading from one end of the coil are an identical set leading from the other end.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] In all, this creates a repeating sequence of four poles, unshaded alternating with shaded, that creates a circumferential traveling field to which the rotor's magnetic poles rapidly synchronize.
[src:dynamo/ac-motor] Some stepping motors have a similar structure.
[src:dynamo/ac-to-ac-converter] A solid-state **AC-to-AC converter** converts an AC waveform to another AC waveform, where the output voltage and frequency can be set arbitrarily.
[src:dynamo/ac-to-ac-converter] Any dynamic braking operation required for the motor can be realized by means of braking DC chopper and resistor shunt connected across the rectifier.
[src:dynamo/ac-to-ac-converter] Alternatively, an anti-parallel thyristor bridge must be provided in the rectifier section to feed energy back into the AC line.
[src:dynamo/ac-to-ac-converter] Such phase-controlled thyristor-based rectifiers however have higher AC line distortion and lower power factor at low load than diode-based rectifiers.
[src:dynamo/ac-to-ac-converter] An AC-AC converter with approximately sinusoidal input currents and bidirectional power flow can be realized by coupling a pulse-width modulation (PWM) rectifier and a PWM inverter to the DC-link.
[src:dynamo/ac-to-ac-converter] The DC-link quantity is then impressed by an energy storage element that is common to both stages, which is a capacitor C for the voltage DC-link or an inductor L for the current DC-link.
[src:dynamo/ac-to-ac-converter] The PWM rectifier is controlled in a way that a sinusoidal AC line current is drawn, which is in phase or anti-phase (for energy feedback) with the corresponding AC line phase voltage.
[src:dynamo/ac-to-ac-converter] Due to the DC-link storage element, there is the advantage that both converter stages are to a large extent decoupled for control purposes.
[src:dynamo/ac-to-ac-converter] Furthermore, a constant, AC line independent input quantity exists for the PWM inverter stage, which results in high utilization of the converter’s power capability.
[src:dynamo/ac-to-ac-converter] On the other hand, the DC-link energy storage element has a relatively large physical volume, and when electrolytic capacitors are used, in the case of a voltage DC-link, there is potentially a reduced system lifetime.
[src:dynamo/ac-to-ac-converter] A cycloconverter constructs an output, variable-frequency, approximately sinusoid waveform by switching segments of the input waveform to the output; there is no intermediate DC link.
[src:dynamo/ac-to-ac-converter] With switching elements such as SCRs, the output frequency must be lower than the input.
[src:dynamo/ac-to-ac-converter] Very large cycloconverters (on the order of 10 MW) are manufactured for compressor and wind-tunnel drives, or for variable-speed applications such as cement kilns.
[src:dynamo/ac-to-ac-converter] In order to achieve higher power density and reliability, matrix converters are considered.
[src:dynamo/ac-to-ac-converter] They achieve three-phase AC-AC conversion without any intermediate energy storage element.
[src:dynamo/ac-to-ac-converter] Conventional direct matrix converters (Fig.
[src:dynamo/ac-to-ac-converter] 4) perform voltage and current conversion in one single stage.
[src:dynamo/ac-to-ac-converter] There is the alternative option of indirect energy conversion by employing the Indirect Matrix Converter (Fig.
[src:dynamo/ac-to-ac-converter] 5) or the Sparse matrix converter which was invented by Prof.
[src:dynamo/ac-to-ac-converter] As with the DC-link based VSI and CSI controllers (Fig.
[src:dynamo/ac-to-ac-converter] 3), separate stages are provided for voltage and current conversion, but the DC-link has no intermediate storage element.
[src:dynamo/ac-to-ac-converter] Generally, by employing matrix converters, the storage element in the DC-link is eliminated at the cost of a larger number of semiconductors.
[src:dynamo/ac-to-ac-converter] Matrix converters are often seen as a future concept for variable speed drives technology, but despite intensive research over the decades they have until now only achieved low industrial penetration.
[src:dynamo/ac-to-ac-converter] However, citing recent availability of low-cost, high performance semiconductors, one larger drive manufacturer has over past few years been actively promoting matrix converters.
[src:dynamo/air-cooling] In all cases, the air has to be cooler than the object or surface from which it is expected to remove heat.
[src:dynamo/air-cooling] This is due to the second law of thermodynamics, which states that heat will only move spontaneously from a hot reservoir (the heat sink) to a cold reservoir (the air).
[src:dynamo/air-cooling] When operating in an environment with lower air pressure like high altitude or airplane cabins, the cooling capacity has to be derated compared to that of sea level.
[src:dynamo/air-cooling] A rule-of-thumb formula to note: 1 – (h/17500) = derating factor.
[src:dynamo/air-cooling] Where *h* is the height over sea level in meters.
[src:dynamo/air-cooling] And the result is the factor that should be multiplied with the cooling capacity in [W] to get the cooling capacity at the specified height over sea level.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] A particulate **air filter** is a device composed of fibrous or porous materials which removes particulates such as smoke, dust, pollen, mold, viruses, and bacteria from the air.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] Filters containing an adsorbent or catalyst such as charcoal (carbon) or baking sodamay also remove odors and gaseous pollutants, such as volatile organic compounds or ozone.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] Air filters are typically constructed of foam, pleated paper, cotton, or spun fiberglass.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] Oil bath air filters have fallen out of favour aside from niche uses.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] Air ionizers use a different method, static electric charge, than air filters to attract and remove dust particles but they may also be supplemented with an air filter.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] High efficiency particulate arrester (HEPA), originally called high-efficiency particulate absorber but also sometimes called high-efficiency particulate arresting or high-efficiency particulate arrestance, is a type of air filter.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] Filters meeting the HEPA standard have many applications, including use in clean rooms for IC fabrication, medical facilities, automobiles, aircraft and homes.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] The filter must satisfy certain standards of efficiency such as those set by the United States Department of Energy (DOE).
[src:dynamo/air-filter] Varying standards define what qualifies as a HEPA filter.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] The two most common standards EN 1822 and ASME AG-1 require an air filter must remove (from the air that passes through) 99.95% (European Standard) or 99.97% (ASME standard) of particles that have a size greater than or equal to 0.3 μm.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] The cabin air filter, also known in the United Kingdom as a pollen filter, is typically a pleated filter that is placed in the outside-air intake for the vehicle's passenger compartment.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] Some of these filters are rectangular, while others are uniquely shaped to fit the available space of particular vehicles' outside-air intakes.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] The first automaker to include a disposable filter to keep the ventilation system clean was the Nash Motors "Weather Eye", introduced in 1940.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] A reusable heater core filter was available as an optional accessory on Studebaker models beginning in 1959, including Studebaker Lark automobiles (1959-1966), Studebaker Gran Turismo Hawk automobiles (1962-1964) and Studebaker Champ trucks (1960-1964).
[src:dynamo/air-filter] The filter was an aluminum frame containing an aluminum mesh and was located directly above the heater core.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] The filter was removed and installed from the engine compartment through a slot in the firewall.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] A long, thin rubber seal plugged the slot when the filter was installed.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] The filter could be vacuumed and washed prior to installation.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] Clogged or dirty cabin air filters can reduce airflow available to the cabin vents, as well as introduce allergens into the cabin air stream.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] Since the cabin air temperature depends upon the flow rate of the air passing through the heater core, the evaporator, or both, clogged filters can greatly reduce the effectiveness and performance of the vehicle's air conditioning and heating systems.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] At the point of retail to the consumer, cabin air filter suppliers do not share performance testing characteristics listed below.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] However, some cabin air filter manufacturers do print a minimum efficiency reporting value (MERV) filter rating or cite N95 (however disclaim any NIOSH compliance) on their cabin air filter retail boxes.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] Pleat spacing (inversely pleat count) of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] Airflow and pressure drop of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] The combustion air filter prevents abrasive particulate matter from entering the engine's cylinders, causing mechanical wear, oil contamination, and change to emissions performance.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] Many modern fuel injected vehicles use a pleated paper filter element in the form of a flat panel, usually placed inside a plastic box connected to the throttle body with duct work.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] The overall unit (filter and housing, and duct work together) is called the **air cleaner**.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] Air intake filter media technology improvements have helped increase overall efficiency of gas turbine air-compressors by using simulation tools to optimize aerodynamics and fluid dynamics.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] Pleated paper filter elements are the nearly exclusive choice for automobile engine air cleaners, because they are efficient, easy to service, and cost-effective.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] The "paper" term is somewhat misleading, as the paper filter media is constructed differently from papers used for writing or packaging, by employing binding resins or surface modifications.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] The paper is pleated/bent in a zig-zag shape to increase the filtration surface area of the paper encountered by the airflow path, in the range of 50 times that of the air opening.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] There is a persistent belief among tuners, reinforced by advertising for aftermarket non-paper replacement filters manufacturers, that paper filters flow poorly enough to restrict engine performance.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] Oil-wetted polyurethane foam elements are used in some aftermarket replacement automobile air filters.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] Foam was in the past widely used in air cleaners on small engines on lawnmowers and other power equipment, but automotive-type paper filter elements have largely supplanted oil-wetted foam in these applications.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] Foam filters are still commonly used on air compressors for air tools up to 5 horsepower (3.7 kW).
[src:dynamo/air-filter] Due to the way dust is captured on foam filters, large amounts may be trapped without measurable change in airflow restriction.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] Oiled cotton gauze is employed in a growing number of aftermarket automotive air filters marketed as high-performance items.[2] In the 1970's, with the introduction of the Fiat Abarth SS versions, cotton gauze air filters as OE automotive engine filters gained market traction.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] Metal Mesh (stainless steel for rust resistance) is another example of an air filter media which can be ordered with different mesh counts to adjust for desired performance characteristics.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] An oil bath air cleaner consists of a sump containing a pool of oil and an insert which is filled with fiber, mesh, foam, or another coarse filter media.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] The cleaner removes particles by adhering them to the oil-soaked filter media; as opposed to traditional filtration, the openings in the filter media are much larger than the particles that are to be filtered.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] When the cleaner is assembled, the media-containing body of the insert sits a short distance above the surface of the oil pool.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] The rim of the insert overlaps the rim of the sump.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] This U-turn takes the air at high velocity across the surface of the oil pool.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] Heavier (and typically larger) dust and dirt particles in the air cannot make the turn due to their inertia, so they fall into the oil and settle to the bottom of the base bowl.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] Lighter (and typically smaller) particles stick to the filtration media in the insert, which is wetted by oil droplets aspirated there by normal airflow.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] The constant aspiration of oil onto the filter media slowly carries most of the finer trapped particles downward and the oil drips back into the reservoir where the particles accumulate.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] Oil bath air cleaners were very widely used in automotive and small engine applications until the widespread industry adoption of the paper filter in the early 1960s.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] Such cleaners are still used in off-road equipment where very high levels of dust are encountered, for oil bath air cleaners can sequester a great deal of dirt relative to their overall size without loss of filtration efficiency or airflow.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] In the early 20th century (about 1900 to 1930), water bath air cleaners were used in some applications (cars, trucks, tractors, and portable and stationary engines).
[src:dynamo/air-filter] They worked on roughly the same principles as oil bath air cleaners.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] For example, the original Fordson tractor had a water bath air cleaner.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] By the 1940s, oil bath designs had displaced water bath designs because of better filtering performance.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] Bulk solids handling involves the transport of solids (mechanical transport, pneumatic transport) which may be in a powder form.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] Many industries are handling bulk solids (mining industries, chemical industries, food industries) which requires the treatment of air streams escaping the process so that fine particles are not emitted, for regulatory reasons or economical reasons (loss of materials).
[src:dynamo/air-filter] As a consequence, air filters are positioned at many places in the process, especially at the reception of pneumatic conveying lines where the quantity of air is important and the load in fine particle quite important.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] Filters can also be placed at any point of air exchange in the process to avoid that pollutants enter the process, which is particularly true in pharmaceuticals and food industries.
[src:dynamo/air-filter] European standard EN 779, on which the above table is based, remained in effect from 2012 to mid-2018, when it was replaced by ISO 16890.
[src:dynamo/airbox] An **airbox** is an empty chamber on the inlet of most combustion engines.
[src:dynamo/airbox] It collects air from outside and feeds it to the intake hoses of each cylinder.
[src:dynamo/airbox] Older engines drew air directly from the surroundings into each individual carburetor.
[src:dynamo/airbox] Modern engines instead draw air into an airbox, which is connected by individual hoses to each carburetor or directly to the intake ports in fuel-injected engines, thus avoiding an extra intake manifold.
[src:dynamo/airbox] The airbox allows the use of one air filter instead of multiples, reducing complexity.
[src:dynamo/airbox] Developments arising from concerns about engine emissions during the late 1970s allow the airbox to collect pump gases from the crankcase and the tank air vent and re-feed them to the engine.
[src:dynamo/airbox] Since the 1990s, engine designers also sought to exploit the properties of oscillating gas to improve performance.
[src:dynamo/airbox] Many high-performance motorcycles have the airbox fed from funnels in the front of the bike, where increased pressure forces more air into the intake and thus improves power.
[src:dynamo/airbox] Examples of this ram-air intake construction are the SRAD models of the Suzuki GSX-R750, the Kawasaki Ninja ZX-6R or the BMW S1000RR.
[src:dynamo/airbox] Secondly, designers exploit a property of air cavities known as Helmholtz resonance.
[src:dynamo/airbox] Flow through the airbox is optimal at its resonance frequency, which depends on airbox volume and the inlet area and length of the snorkel.
[src:dynamo/airbox] The resonance is typically chosen to be at a medium speed where torque otherwise drops, caused by valve timing overlap.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] The usual waveform of alternating current in most electric power circuits is a sine wave, whose positive half-period corresponds with positive direction of the current and vice versa (the full period is called a *cycle*).
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] "Alternating current" most commonly refers to power distribution, but a wide range of other applications are technically alternating current although it is less common to describe them by that term.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] In many applications, like guitar amplifiers, different waveforms are used, such as triangular waves or square waves.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Audio and radio signals carried on electrical wires are also examples of alternating current.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] These types of alternating current carry information such as sound (audio) or images (video) sometimes carried by modulation of an AC carrier signal.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] These currents typically alternate at higher frequencies than those used in power transmission.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Electrical energy is distributed as alternating current because AC voltage may be increased or decreased with a transformer.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] This allows the power to be transmitted through power lines efficiently at high voltage, which reduces the energy lost as heat due to resistance of the wire, and transformed to a lower, safer voltage for use.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Use of a higher voltage leads to significantly more efficient transmission of power.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] This means that when transmitting a fixed power on a given wire, if the current is halved (by doubling the voltage), the power loss due to the wire's resistance will be reduced by a factor of four.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Consequently, power transmitted at a higher voltage requires less loss-producing current than for the same power at a lower voltage.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Power is often transmitted at hundreds of kilovolts on pylons, and transformed down to tens of kilovolts to be transmitted on lower level lines, and finally transformed down to 100 V – 240 V for domestic use.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] High voltages have disadvantages, such as the increased insulation required, and generally increased difficulty in their safe handling.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] In a power plant, energy is generated at a convenient voltage for the design of a generator, and then stepped up to a high voltage for transmission.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Near the loads, the transmission voltage is stepped down to the voltages used by equipment.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Consumer voltages vary somewhat depending on the country and size of load, but generally motors and lighting are built to use up to a few hundred volts between phases.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] The voltage delivered to equipment such as lighting and motor loads is standardized, with an allowable range of voltage over which equipment is expected to operate.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Standard power utilization voltages and percentage tolerance vary in the different mains power systems found in the world.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] High-voltage direct-current (HVDC) electric power transmission systems have become more viable as technology has provided efficient means of changing the voltage of DC power.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Transmission with high voltage direct current was not feasible in the early days of electric power transmission, as there was then no economically viable way to step the voltage of DC down for end user applications such as lighting incandescent bulbs.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Three-phase electrical generation is very common.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] The simplest way is to use three separate coils in the generator stator, physically offset by an angle of 120° (one-third of a complete 360° phase) to each other.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Three current waveforms are produced that are equal in magnitude and 120° out of phase to each other.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] If coils are added opposite to these (60° spacing), they generate the same phases with reverse polarity and can be wired together.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] In practice, higher *pole orders* are commonly used.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] For example, a 12-pole machine would have 36 coils (10° spacing).
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] The advantage is that lower rotational speeds can be used to generate the same frequency.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] For example, a 2-pole machine running at 3600 rpm and a 12-pole machine running at 600 rpm produce the same frequency; the lower speed is preferable for larger machines.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] If the load on a three-phase system is balanced equally among the phases, no current flows through the neutral point.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Even in the worst-case unbalanced (linear) load, the neutral current will not exceed the highest of the phase currents.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Non-linear loads (e.g. the switch-mode power supplies widely used) may require an oversized neutral bus and neutral conductor in the upstream distribution panel to handle harmonics.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Harmonics can cause neutral conductor current levels to exceed that of one or all phase conductors.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] For three-phase at utilization voltages a four-wire system is often used.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] When stepping down three-phase, a transformer with a Delta (3-wire) primary and a Star (4-wire, center-earthed) secondary is often used so there is no need for a neutral on the supply side.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] For smaller customers (just how small varies by country and age of the installation) only a single phase and neutral, or two phases and neutral, are taken to the property.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] For larger installations, all three phases and neutral are taken to the main distribution panel.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] From the three-phase main panel, both single and three-phase circuits may lead off.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Three-wire single-phase systems, with a single center-tapped transformer giving two live conductors, is a common distribution scheme for residential and small commercial buildings in North America.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] This arrangement is sometimes incorrectly referred to as *two phase*.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] A similar method is used for a different reason on construction sites in the UK.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Small power tools and lighting are supposed to be supplied by a local center-tapped transformer with a voltage of 55 V between each power conductor and earth.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] This significantly reduces the risk of electric shock in the event that one of the live conductors becomes exposed through an equipment fault whilst still allowing a reasonable voltage of 110 V between the two conductors for running the tools.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] An additional wire, called the bond (or earth) wire, is often connected between non-current-carrying metal enclosures and earth ground.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] This conductor provides protection from electric shock due to accidental contact of circuit conductors with the metal chassis of portable appliances and tools.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Bonding all non-current-carrying metal parts into one complete system ensures there is always a low electrical impedance path to ground sufficient to carry any fault current for as long as it takes for the system to clear the fault.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] This low impedance path allows the maximum amount of fault current, causing the overcurrent protection device (breakers, fuses) to trip or burn out as quickly as possible, bringing the electrical system to a safe state.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] All bond wires are bonded to ground at the main service panel, as is the neutral/identified conductor if present.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] The frequency of the electrical system varies by country and sometimes within a country; most electric power is generated at either 50 or 60 Hz.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Some countries have a mixture of 50 Hz and 60 Hz supplies, notably electricity power transmission in Japan.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] A low frequency eases the design of electric motors, particularly for hoisting, crushing and rolling applications, and commutator-type traction motors for applications such as railways.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] However, low frequency also causes noticeable flicker in arc lamps and incandescent light bulbs.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] The use of lower frequencies also provided the advantage of lower transmission losses, which are proportional to frequency.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls generators were built to produce 25 Hz power, as a compromise between low frequency for traction and heavy induction motors, while still allowing incandescent lighting to operate (although with noticeable flicker).
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Most of the 25 Hz residential and commercial customers for Niagara Falls power were converted to 60 Hz by the late 1950s, although some 25 Hz industrial customers still existed as of the start of the 21st century.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] 16.7 Hz power (formerly 16 2/3 Hz) is still used in some European rail systems, such as in Austria, Germany, Norway, Sweden and Switzerland.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Off-shore, military, textile industry, marine, aircraft, and spacecraft applications sometimes use 400 Hz, for benefits of reduced weight of apparatus or higher motor speeds.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Computer mainframe systems were often powered by 400 Hz or 415 Hz for benefits of ripple reduction while using smaller internal AC to DC conversion units.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] A direct current flows uniformly throughout the cross-section of a homogeneous electrically conducting wire.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] An alternating current of any frequency is forced away from the wire's center, toward its outer surface.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] This is because an alternating current (which is the result of the acceleration of electric charge) creates electromagnetic waves (a phenomenon known as electromagnetic radiation).
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] The phenomenon of alternating current being pushed away from the center of the conductor is called skin effect, and a direct current does not exhibit this effect, since a direct current does not create electromagnetic waves.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] At very high frequencies, the current no longer flows *in* the wire, but effectively flows *on* the surface of the wire, within a thickness of a few skin depths.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] The skin depth is the thickness at which the current density is reduced by 63%.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Even at relatively low frequencies used for power transmission (50 Hz – 60 Hz), non-uniform distribution of current still occurs in sufficiently thick conductors.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] For example, the skin depth of a copper conductor is approximately 8.57 mm at 60 Hz, so high-current conductors are usually hollow to reduce their mass and cost.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] This tendency of alternating current to flow predominantly in the periphery of conductors reduces the effective cross-section of the conductor.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] This increases the effective AC resistance of the conductor since resistance is inversely proportional to the cross-sectional area.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] A conductor's AC resistance is higher than its DC resistance, causing a higher energy loss due to Ohmic heating (also called I2R loss).
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] For low to medium frequencies, conductors can be divided into stranded wires, each insulated from the others, with the relative positions of individual strands specially arranged within the conductor bundle.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Wire constructed using this technique is called Litz wire.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] This measure helps to partially mitigate skin effect by forcing more equal current throughout the total cross section of the stranded conductors.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] As written above, an alternating current is made of electric charge under periodic acceleration, which causes radiation of electromagnetic waves.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Depending on the frequency, different techniques are used to minimize the loss due to radiation.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] At frequencies up to about 1 GHz, pairs of wires are twisted together in a cable, forming a twisted pair.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] This reduces losses from electromagnetic radiation and inductive coupling.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] A twisted pair must be used with a balanced signaling system so that the two wires carry equal but opposite currents.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Each wire in a twisted pair radiates a signal, but it is effectively canceled by radiation from the other wire, resulting in almost no radiation loss.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Coaxial cables are commonly used at audio frequencies and above for convenience.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] A coaxial cable has a conductive wire inside a conductive tube, separated by a dielectric layer.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] The current flowing on the surface of the inner conductor is equal and opposite to the current flowing on the inner surface of the outer tube.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] The electromagnetic field is thus completely contained within the tube, and (ideally) no energy is lost to radiation or coupling outside the tube.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Coaxial cables have acceptably small losses for frequencies up to about 5 GHz.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] For microwave frequencies greater than 5 GHz, the losses (due mainly to the dielectric separating the inner and outer tubes being a non-ideal insulator) become too large, making waveguides a more efficient medium for transmitting energy.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Coaxial cables often use a perforated dielectric layer to separate the inner and outer conductors in order to minimize the power dissipated by the dielectric.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Waveguides are similar to coaxial cables, as both consist of tubes, with the biggest difference being that waveguides have no inner conductor.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Waveguides can have any arbitrary cross section, but rectangular cross sections are the most common.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Because waveguides do not have an inner conductor to carry a return current, waveguides cannot deliver energy by means of an electric current, but rather by means of a *guided* electromagnetic field.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Although surface currents do flow on the inner walls of the waveguides, those surface currents do not carry power.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Power is carried by the guided electromagnetic fields.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] The surface currents are set up by the guided electromagnetic fields and have the effect of keeping the fields inside the waveguide and preventing leakage of the fields to the space outside the waveguide.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Waveguides have dimensions comparable to the wavelength of the alternating current to be transmitted, so they are feasible only at microwave frequencies.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] In addition to this mechanical feasibility, electrical resistance of the non-ideal metals forming the walls of the waveguide causes dissipation of power (surface currents flowing on lossy conductors dissipate power).
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] At higher frequencies, the power lost to this dissipation becomes unacceptably large.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] At frequencies greater than 200 GHz, waveguide dimensions become impractically small, and the ohmic losses in the waveguide walls become large.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Instead, fiber optics, which are a form of dielectric waveguides, can be used.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] For such frequencies, the concepts of voltages and currents are no longer used.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Alternating currents are accompanied (or caused) by alternating voltages.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] The peak-to-peak value of an AC voltage is defined as the difference between its positive peak and its negative peak.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Since the maximum value of $\sin(x)$ is +1 and the minimum value is −1, an AC voltage swings between $+V_{\text{peak}}$ and $-V_{\text{peak}}$ .
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Below an AC waveform (with no DC component) is assumed.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] The RMS voltage is the square root of the mean over one cycle of the square of the instantaneous voltage.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Rather than using instantaneous power, $p(t)$ , it is more practical to use a time-averaged power (where the averaging is performed over any integer number of cycles).
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] For this reason, AC power's waveform becomes Full-wave rectified sine, and its fundamental frequency is double that of the voltage's.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] To illustrate these concepts, consider a 230 V AC mains supply used in many countries around the world.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] It is so called because its root mean square value is 230 V.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] This means that the time-averaged power delivered $P_{\text{average}}$ is equivalent to the power delivered by a DC voltage of 230 V.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] For 230 V AC, the peak voltage $V_{\text{peak}}$ is therefore $230{\text{ V}}\times {\sqrt {2}}$ , which is about 325 V, and the peak power $P_{\text{peak}}$ is $230\times R\times W\times 2$ , that is 460 RW.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] During the course of one cycle (two cycle as the power) the voltage rises from zero to 325 V, the power from zero to 460 RW, and both falls through zero.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Next, the voltage descends to reverse direction, −325 V, but the power ascends again to 460 RW, and both returns to zero.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Alternating current is used to transmit information, as in the cases of telephone and cable television.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Information signals are carried over a wide range of AC frequencies.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] POTS telephone signals have a frequency of about 3 kHz, close to the baseband audio frequency.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Cable television and other cable-transmitted information currents may alternate at frequencies of tens to thousands of megahertz.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] These frequencies are similar to the electromagnetic wave frequencies often used to transmit the same types of information over the air.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] The first alternator to produce alternating current was an electric generator based on Michael Faraday's principles constructed by the French instrument maker Hippolyte Pixii in 1832.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Pixii later added a commutator to his device to produce the (then) more commonly used direct current.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] The earliest recorded practical application of alternating current is by Guillaume Duchenne, inventor and developer of electrotherapy.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] In 1855, he announced that AC was superior to direct current for electrotherapeutic triggering of muscle contractions.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Alternating current technology was developed further by the Hungarian Ganz Works company in the 1870s, and, in the 1880s, by Sebastian Ziani de Ferranti, Lucien Gaulard, and Galileo Ferraris.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] In 1876, Russian engineer Pavel Yablochkov invented a lighting system where sets of induction coils were installed along a high-voltage AC line.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Instead of changing voltage, the primary windings transferred power to the secondary windings which were connected to one or several electric candles (arc lamps) of his own design, used to keep the failure of one lamp from disabling the entire circuit.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] In 1878, the Ganz factory, Budapest, Hungary, began manufacturing equipment for electric lighting and, by 1883, had installed over fifty systems in Austria-Hungary.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Their AC systems used arc and incandescent lamps, generators, and other equipment.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] The development of the alternating current transformer to change voltage from low to high level and back, allowed generation and consumption at low voltages and transmission, over great distances, at high voltage, with savings in the cost of conductors and energy losses.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] A bipolar open-core power transformer developed by Lucien Gaulard and John Dixon Gibbs was demonstrated in London in 1881, and attracted the interest of Westinghouse.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] They exhibited an AC system powering arc and incandescent lights was installed along five railway stations for the Metropolitan Railway in London and a single-phase multiple-user AC distribution system Turin in 1884.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] These early induction coils with open magnetic circuits were inefficient at transferring power to loads.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Until about 1880, the paradigm for AC power transmission from a high voltage supply to a low voltage load was a series circuit.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Open-core transformers with a ratio near 1:1 were connected with their primaries in series to allow use of a high voltage for transmission while presenting a low voltage to the lamps.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] The inherent flaw in this method was that turning off a single lamp (or other electronic device) affected the voltage supplied to all others on the same circuit.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Many adjustable transformer designs were introduced to compensate for this problematic characteristic of the series circuit, including those employing methods of adjusting the core or bypassing the magnetic flux around part of a coil.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] The direct current systems did not have these drawbacks, giving it significant advantages over early AC systems.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] In 1890, he designed their power station at Deptford and converted the Grosvenor Gallery station across the Thames into an electrical substation, showing the way to integrate older plants into a universal AC supply system.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] In the autumn of 1884, Károly Zipernowsky, Ottó Bláthy and Miksa Déri (ZBD), three engineers associated with the Ganz Works of Budapest, determined that open-core devices were impractical, as they were incapable of reliably regulating voltage.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] In both designs, the magnetic flux linking the primary and secondary windings traveled almost entirely within the confines of the iron core, with no intentional path through air (see toroidal cores).
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] The new transformers were 3.4 times more efficient than the open-core bipolar devices of Gaulard and Gibbs.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] The Ganz factory in 1884 shipped the world's first five high-efficiency AC transformers.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] This first unit had been manufactured to the following specifications: 1,400 W, 40 Hz, 120:72 V, 11.6:19.4 A, ratio 1.67:1, one-phase, shell form.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] When employed in parallel connected electric distribution systems, closed-core transformers finally made it technically and economically feasible to provide electric power for lighting in homes, businesses and public spaces.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] The other essential milestone was the introduction of 'voltage source, voltage intensive' (VSVI) systems' by the invention of constant voltage generators in 1885.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] In early 1885, the three engineers also eliminated the problem of eddy current losses with the invention of the lamination of electromagnetic cores.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Ottó Bláthy also invented the first AC electricity meter.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] In May 1885, at the Hungarian National Exhibition in Budapest, Deri, Blathy, and Zipernowski held a large-scale demonstration of what is widely regarded as the prototype of modern AC lighting systems.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Their system used 75 transformers in parallel connection, supplying 1,067 incandescent Edison lamps from an AC generator that provided 1,350 V.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] The AC power system was developed and adopted rapidly after 1886.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] With this setup, the Westinghouse company successfully powered thirty 100-volt incandescent bulbs in twenty shops along the main street of Great Barrington.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] By the fall of that year Ganz engineers installed a ZBD transformer power system with AC generators in Rome.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Based on Stanley's success, the new Westinghouse Electric went on to develop alternating current (AC) electric infrastructure throughout the United States.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] The spread of Westinghouse and other AC systems triggered a push back in late 1887 by Thomas Edison (a proponent of direct current), who attempted to discredit alternating current as too dangerous in a public campaign called the "war of the currents".
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] In 1888, alternating current systems gained further viability with the introduction of a functional AC motor, something these systems had lacked up till then.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] The design, an induction motor, was independently invented by Galileo Ferraris and Nikola Tesla (with Tesla's design being licensed by Westinghouse in the US).
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] This design was independently further developed into the modern practical three-phase form by Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrovolsky and Charles Eugene Lancelot Brown in Germany on one side, and Jonas Wenström in Sweden on the other, though Brown favored the two-phase system.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] The Ames Hydroelectric Generating Plant, constructed in 1890, was among the first hydroelectric alternating current power plants.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] A long-distance transmission of single-phase electricity from a hydroelectric generating plant in Oregon at Willamette Falls sent power fourteen miles downriver to downtown Portland for street lighting in 1890.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] In 1891, another transmission system was installed in Telluride Colorado.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] The first three-phase system was established in 1891 in Frankfurt, Germany.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] The Tivoli–Rome transmission was completed in 1892.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] The San Antonio Canyon Generator was the third commercial single-phase hydroelectric AC power plant in the United States to provide long-distance electricity.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] It was completed on December 31, 1892, by Almarian William Decker to provide power to the city of Pomona, California, which was 14 miles away.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Meanwhile, the possibility of transferring electrical power from a waterfall at a distance was explored at the Grängesberg mine in Sweden.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] A 45 m fall at Hällsjön, Smedjebackens kommun, where a small iron work had been located, was selected.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] In 1893, a three-phase 9.5 kv system was used to transfer 400 horsepower a distance of 15 km, becoming the first commercial application.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] In 1893, Westinghouse built an alternating current system for the Chicago World Exposition.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] In 1893, Decker designed the first American commercial three-phase power plant using alternating current—the hydroelectric Mill Creek No.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] 1 Hydroelectric Plant near Redlands, California.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Decker's design incorporated 10 kV three-phase transmission and established the standards for the complete system of generation, transmission and motors used in USA today.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls Adams Power Plant with three two-phase generators was put into operation in August 1895, but was connected to the remote transmission system only in 1896.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] The Jaruga Hydroelectric Power Plant in Croatia was set in operation two days later, on 28 August 1895.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Its generator (42 Hz, 240 kW) was made and installed by the Hungarian company Ganz, while the transmission line from the power plant to the City of Šibenik was 11.5 kilometers (7.1 mi) long, and the municipal distribution grid 3000 V/110 V included six transforming stations.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Alternating current circuit theory developed rapidly in the latter part of the 19th and early 20th century.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Notable contributors to the theoretical basis of alternating current calculations include Charles Steinmetz, Oliver Heaviside, and many others.
[src:dynamo/alternating-current] Calculations in unbalanced three-phase systems were simplified by the symmetrical components methods discussed by Charles LeGeyt Fortescue in 1918.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] A **dynamo** is an electrical generator that creates direct current using a commutator, and uses self-powering electromagnets for the stator field rather than permanent magnets.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] Dynamos are self-starting by using residual magnetic field left in the iron cores of the electromagnets (i.e. field coils).
[src:dynamo/dynamo] If a dynamo were never run before, it was usual to use a separate battery to excite or *flash the field* of the electromagnets to enable self-starting.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] Dynamos were the first practical electrical generators capable of delivering power for industry, and the foundation upon which many other later electric-power conversion devices were based, including the electric motor, the alternating-current alternator, and the rotary converter.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] Today, the simpler and more reliable alternator dominates large scale power generation, for efficiency, reliability and cost reasons.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] A dynamo has the disadvantages of a mechanical commutator.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] Also, converting alternating to direct current using rectifiers (such as vacuum tubes or more recently via solid state technology) is effective and usually economical.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] The operating principle of electromagnetic generators was discovered in the years 1831–1832 by Michael Faraday.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] The principle, later called Faraday's law, is that an electromotive force is generated in an electrical conductor which encircles a varying magnetic flux.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] He also built the first electromagnetic generator, called the Faraday disk, a type of homopolar generator, using a copper disc rotating between the poles of a horseshoe magnet.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] This was not a dynamo in the current sense, because it did not use a commutator.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] This counterflow limited the power output to the pickup wires, and induced waste heating of the copper disc.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] Faraday and others found that higher, more useful voltages could be produced by winding multiple turns of wire into a coil.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] Wire windings can conveniently produce any voltage desired by changing the number of turns, so they have been a feature of all subsequent generator designs, requiring the invention of the commutator to produce direct current.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] The first commutated dynamo was built in 1832 by Hippolyte Pixii, a French instrument maker.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] It used a permanent magnet which was rotated by a crank.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] The spinning magnet was positioned so that its north and south poles passed by a piece of iron wrapped with insulated wire.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] Pixii found that the spinning magnet produced a pulse of current in the wire each time a pole passed the coil.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] However, the north and south poles of the magnet induced currents in opposite directions.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] To convert the alternating current to DC, Pixii invented a commutator, a split metal cylinder on the shaft, with two springy metal contacts that pressed against it.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] This early design had a problem: the electric current it produced consisted of a series of "spikes" or pulses of current separated by none at all, resulting in a low average power output.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] As with electric motors of the period, the designers did not fully realize the seriously detrimental effects of large air gaps in the magnetic circuit.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] This meant that some part of the coil was continually passing by the magnets, smoothing out the current.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] In 1827, independently of Faraday, Hungarian inventor Ányos Jedlik started experimenting with electromagnetic rotating devices which he called electromagnetic self-rotors.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] In the prototype of the single-pole electric starter, both the stationary and the revolving parts were electromagnetic.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] Around 1856, six years before Siemens and Wheatstone, Jedlik formulated the concept of the dynamo, but did not patent it as he thought he was not the first to realize the idea.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] Instead of permanent magnets, his dynamo used two electromagnets placed opposite to each other in order to induce a magnetic field around the rotor.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] This was also the discovery of the principle of dynamo self-excitation, which replaced permanent magnet designs.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] The modern dynamo, fit for use in industrial applications, was invented by Henry Wilde with his paper presented to The Royal Society by Michael Faraday on 26th March 1866.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] It was independently invented by Sir Charles Wheatstone, Werner von Siemens and Samuel Alfred Varley.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] Varley took out a patent on 24 December 1866, while Siemens and Wheatstone both announced their discoveries on 17 January 1867, by delivering papers at the Royal Society.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] Zénobe Gramme reinvented Pacinotti's design in 1871 when designing the first commercial power plants operated in Paris.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] An advantage of Gramme's design was a better path for the magnetic flux, by filling the space occupied by the magnetic field with heavy iron cores and minimizing the air gaps between the stationary and rotating parts.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] The Gramme dynamo was one of the first machines to generate commercial quantities of power for industry.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] Further improvements were made on the Gramme ring, but the basic concept of a spinning endless loop of wire remains at the heart of all modern dynamos.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] Brush assembled his first dynamo in the summer of 1876 using a horse-drawn treadmill to power it.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] Brush's design modified the Gramme dynamo by shaping the ring armature like a disc rather than a cylinder shape.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] The field electromagnets were also positioned on the sides of the armature disc rather than around the circumference.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] They were multi-field single-rotor devices with two or more sets of rotating contacts (either commutators or sliprings, as required), one to provide power to one set of armature windings to turn the device, and one or more attached to other windings to produce the output current.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] The rotary converter can directly convert, internally, any type of electric power into any other.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] This includes converting between direct current (DC) and alternating current (AC), three phase and single phase power, 25 Hz AC and 60 Hz AC, or many different output voltages at the same time.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] The size and mass of the rotor was made large so that the rotor would act as a flywheel to help smooth out any sudden surges or dropouts in the applied power.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] The technology of rotary converters was replaced in the early 20th century by mercury-vapor rectifiers, which were smaller, did not produce vibration and noise, and required less maintenance.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] The same conversion tasks are now performed by solid state power semiconductor devices.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] Rotary converters remained in use in the West Side IRT subway in Manhattan into the late 1960s, and possibly some years later.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] They were powered by 25 Hz AC, and provided DC at 600 volts for the trains.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] Direct current machines like dynamos and commutated DC motors have higher maintenance costs and power limitations than alternating current (AC) machines due to their use of the commutator.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] Although direct current dynamos were the first source of electric power for industry, they had to be located close to the factories that used their power.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] Electricity could only be distributed over distances economically as alternating current (AC), through the use of the transformer.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] With the 1890s conversion of electric power systems to alternating current, during the 20th century dynamos were replaced by alternators, and are now almost obsolete.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] The word 'dynamo' (from the Greek word *dynamis* (δύναμις), meaning force or power) was originally another name for an electrical generator, and still has some regional usage as a replacement for the word generator.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] The word was coined in 1831 by Michael Faraday, who utilized his invention toward making many discoveries in electricity (Faraday discovered electrical induction) and magnetism.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] The original "dynamo principle" of Werner von Siemens referred only to the direct current generators which use exclusively the self-excitation (self-induction) principle to generate DC power.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] The earlier DC generators which used permanent magnets were not considered "dynamo electric machines".
[src:dynamo/dynamo] The invention of the dynamo principle (self-induction) was a major technological leap over the old traditional permanent magnet based DC generators.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] The discovery of the dynamo principle made industrial scale electric power generation technically and economically feasible.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] A small electrical generator built into the hub of a bicycle wheel to power lights is called a hub dynamo, although these are invariably AC devices, and are actually magnetos.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] The electric dynamo uses rotating coils of wire and magnetic fields to convert mechanical rotation into a pulsing direct electric current through Faraday's law of induction.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] A dynamo machine consists of a stationary structure, called the stator, which provides a constant magnetic field, and a set of rotating windings called the armature which turn within that field.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] Due to Faraday's law of induction, the motion of the wire within the magnetic field creates an electromotive force, which pushes on the electrons in the metal, creating an electric current in the wire.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] On small machines, the constant magnetic field may be provided by one or more permanent magnets; larger machines have the constant magnetic field provided by one or more electromagnets, which are usually called *field coils*.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] The *commutator* is needed to produce direct current.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] When a loop of wire rotates in a magnetic field, the magnetic flux through it—and thus the potential induced in it—reverses with each half turn, generating an alternating current.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] However, in the early days of electric experimentation, alternating current generally had no known use.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] The few uses for electricity, such as electroplating, used direct current provided by messy liquid batteries.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] Dynamos were invented as a replacement for batteries.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] The commutator is essentially a rotary switch.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] It consists of a set of contacts mounted on the machine's shaft, combined with graphite-block stationary contacts, called "brushes," because the earliest such fixed contacts were metal brushes.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] The commutator reverses the connection of the windings to the external circuit when the potential reverses — so instead of alternating current, a pulsing direct current is produced.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] The earliest dynamos used permanent magnets to create the magnetic field.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] These were referred to as "magneto-electric machines" or magnetos.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] However, researchers found that stronger magnetic fields — and thus more power — could be produced by using electromagnets (field coils) on the stator.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] These were called "dynamo-electric machines" or dynamos.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] The field coils of the stator were originally *separately excited* by a separate, smaller, dynamo or magneto.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] An important development by Wilde and Siemens was the discovery (by 1866) that a dynamo could also bootstrap itself to be *self-excited*, using current generated by the dynamo itself.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] This allowed the growth of a much more powerful field, thus far greater output power.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] Self-excited direct current dynamos commonly have a combination of series and parallel (shunt) field windings, which are directly supplied power by the rotor through the commutator in a regenerative manner.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] They are started and operated in a manner similar to modern portable alternating current electric generators, which are not used with other generators on an electric grid.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] At the very first run the dynamo machine is started by using external source of current such as battery.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] When it was not operating a residual weak magnetic field always persisted in the iron cores of electromagnets.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] As the dynamo's rotor begun to rotate while not connected to an external load the residual magnetic field induced a very small electrical current into the rotor windings which in turn was supplied back to electromagnet windings.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] Even without an external load attached, this small current was enough to produce a magnetic field causing the rotor to produce even more current.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] In this manner, the self-exciting dynamo *builds up* its internal magnetic fields until it reaches its normal operating voltage.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] When it is able to produce sufficient current to sustain both its internal fields and an external load, it is ready to be used.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] A self-excited dynamo with insufficient residual magnetic field in the metal frame will not be able to produce any current in the rotor, regardless of what speed the rotor spins.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] This situation can also occur in modern self-excited portable generators, and is resolved for both types of generators in a similar manner, by applying a brief direct current battery charge to the output terminals of the stopped generator.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] The battery energizes the windings just enough to imprint the residual field, to enable building up the current.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] This is referred to as *flashing the field*.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] Both types of self-excited generator, which have been attached to a large external load while it was stationary, will not be able to build up voltage even if the residual field is present.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] The load acts as an energy sink and continuously drains away the small rotor current produced by the residual field, preventing magnetic field buildup in the field coil.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] Dynamos, usually driven by steam engines, were widely used in power stations to generate electricity for industrial and domestic purposes.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] They have since been replaced by alternators.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] Large industrial dynamos with series and parallel (shunt) windings can be difficult to use together in a power plant, unless either the rotor or field wiring or the mechanical drive systems are coupled together in certain special combinations.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] Dynamos were used in motor vehicles to generate electricity for battery charging.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] An early type was the third-brush dynamo.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] They have, again, been replaced by alternators, which are automatic versions of the dynamo.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] Dynamos still have some uses in low power applications, particularly where low voltage DC is required, since an alternator with a semiconductor rectifier can be inefficient in these applications.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] Hand cranked dynamos are used in clockwork radios, hand powered flashlights and other human powered equipment to recharge batteries.
[src:dynamo/dynamo] The generator used for bicycle lighting may be called a "dynamo" but these are almost always AC devices and so, strictly, would be called "alternators".
